Forecasting with Fb Prophet¶

We use footfal data from the streets of York (open-source dataset from https://data.yorkopendata.org/dataset/footfall) to test the ForecastProphet class. For test purpose, only a subset of the dataset is used (Coney Street, last 120 days). Data split in training / test sets, z-scored, and UK holidays are added before fitting the model. Footfall forecast is plotted along with goodness of fit and residual plots.

In [2]:
            package_path = os.path.dirname(mltoolbox.__file__).replace(os.path.sep + 'lib' + os.path.sep,
                                                                       os.path.sep + 'Lib' + os.path.sep)

            # data = pd.read_csv(r'./datasets/footfallhourly.csv')
            filepath = package_path + os.path.join(os.sep, 'datasets', 'footfallhourly.csv')
            print(filepath)
            data = pd.read_csv(filepath)
            data = data[data['LocationName'] == 'Coney Street'][
                ['Date', 'TotalCount']
            ].copy()
            
            data = data.tail(24 * 120)  # keep 120 days
            data.Date = pd.to_datetime(data.Date, format='%d/%m/%Y %H:%M:%S').dt.strftime(
                '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'
            )
            data.index = data.Date
            data = data.drop(columns=['Date'])

            # convert to dset
            ds = dset(data=data, target=['TotalCount'])

            (ds
             .remove_nan_rows(any_nan=True)
             .split_train_test_sets(train_test_split=0.2, shuffle_split=False, seed=0)
             .normalize(columns=[ds.target], type='zscore')
             .summary()
             )


            ff = ForecastProphet(
                input_dset=ds, input_y_column='TotalCount',input_ds_column='index'
            )

            ff.add_country_holidays(country_name='UK')

            ff.evaluate_train_test()

Classifiers¶

This section demos:

  • Dset - a "dataset" class that incorporates methods for data cleaning and normalization, train/test spleating, PCA, and more.
  • Hyperoptimizer - which takes multiple sklearn-like classifiers and a list of parameter ranges and finds the best combination to maximize accuracy.
  • Tsne - a class that first fits t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) to the training data, then uses Keras to learn the embedding and apply it to new (test) data.

Classification dataset¶

Generated using sklearn's make_classification: 1000 samples, 4 classes, 10 features (6 information features, 4 redundant features).

In [4]:
#         data = sns.load_dataset('iris')
    
        from sklearn.datasets import make_classification
        X1, Y1 = make_classification(n_samples=1000, n_features=10, n_redundant=4, n_informative=6,
                                     n_clusters_per_class=1, n_classes=4)
        data = pd.DataFrame(X1, columns=['feat' + str(i) for i in range(X1.shape[1])])
        data_labels = pd.DataFrame(Y1, columns=['target'])
        data = data.join(data_labels)
        ds = dset(data, target=["target"], header=0, target_type='')

Dset class¶

Put the data in the "dset" class, split it in 50-50% train and test sets, and normalize it.

In [5]:
        ds = dset(data, target=["target"], header=0, target_type='')

        (ds
         .remove_nan_rows(columns=[ds.target], any_nan=True)
         .remove_nan_columns(any_nan=True)
         .categorical2numeric(exclude_target_column=False)
         .split_train_test_sets(train_test_split=0.5, shuffle_split=True, seed=0)
         .normalize(type='robust')
         .summary()
         )

Hyperoptimizer¶

First we attempt the classification on the high-dimensional data set. The hyperoptimizer is tested on 5 classifiers: Random Forest (rf), Multi-layer peceptron (MLP), XGboost (xgb) and Gaussian Process Classifier (gpc), k-nearest neighbours (knn).

t-SNE¶

First we need to make sure t-SNE provides a good separation of classes in the low dimensional spaces. This is done by tuning t-SNE parameters and re-fitting.
